  "prompt": "Why do headphones always go bad with one ear speaker or the other working only when holding the wire in a certain way?",
  "response": "Headphone issues with intermittent sound are typically caused by several common problems:\n\n1. Wire damage\n- Constant bending and movement causes internal wire breaks\n- Copper wires inside the cable can fracture from repeated stress\n- Especially common near the jack or where the wire meets the headphone housing\n\n2. Connection points\n- Solder joints at the jack or speaker can become loose or corroded\n- Frequent plugging/unplugging causes micro-damage\n- Jack connection points are particularly vulnerable\n\n3. Strain relief weakness\n- The rubber/plastic area where the wire meets the jack or headphone\n- Repeated bending weakens this junction\n- Creates internal wire separation\n\n4. Quality of manufacturing\n- Cheaper headphones use lower-quality materials\n- Thinner, more fragile wires\n- Less robust internal connections\n\n5. Physical stress\n- Wrapping headphones tightly\n- Pulling by the wire instead of the plug\n- Stuffing in bags/pockets\n- Dropping or sitting on them\n\nPrevention tips:\n- Handle carefully\n- Unplug by the jack, not the wire\n- Use cable management/storage\n- Invest in higher-quality headphones\n- Consider models with replaceable cables\n\nThese factors explain why headphones often develop sound issues in one ear over time.",
